{"parse":{"title":"Refusal to serve in a public office","pageid":36481700,"revid":846621949,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p><b>Refusal to serve in a public office</b> is an offence under the <a href=\"/wiki/Common_law\" title=\"Common law\">common law</a> of <a href=\"/wiki/England_and_Wales\" title=\"England and Wales\">England and Wales</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-lawcom_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-lawcom-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-halsbury11_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-halsbury11-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-halsbury469_3-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-halsbury469-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> The offence is currently regarded as obsolete, and it may extend only to the appointment of <a href=\"/wiki/High_sheriff\" title=\"High sheriff\">high sheriffs</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-halsbury11_2-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-halsbury11-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> As a common law offence, it is tried on indictment and can be punished by an unlimited fine and/or period of imprisonment.<sup id=\"cite_ref-halsbury469_3-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-halsbury469-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Members of the <a href=\"/wiki/House_of_Commons_of_the_United_Kingdom\" title=\"House of Commons of the United Kingdom\">House of Commons of the United Kingdom</a> or candidates for election are exempt from the requirement to accept public office where it would cause them to be disqualified from being MPs, although this exemption does not extend to requirements to serve in the armed forces.<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> \n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Refusal_to_serve_in_a_public_office&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-lawcom-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-lawcom_1-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20110602093854/http://www.justice.gov.uk/lawcommission/docs/cp193_Simplification_Public_Nuisance_Consultation.pdf\">\"Simplification of Criminal Law: Public Nuisance and Outraging Public Decency (Consultation Paper No 193)\"</a> <span style=\"font-size:85%;\">(PDF)</span>. <a href=\"/wiki/Law_Commission\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Law Commission\">Law Commission</a>. Archived from <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.justice.gov.uk/lawcommission/docs/cp193_Simplification_Public_Nuisance_Consultation.pdf\">the original</a> <span style=\"font-size:85%;\">(PDF)</span> on 2 June 2011<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">7 February</span> 2011</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=Simplification+of+Criminal+Law%3A+Public+Nuisance+and+Outraging+Public+Decency+%28Consultation+Paper+No+193%29&amp;rft.pub=Law+Commission&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.justice.gov.uk%2Flawcommission%2Fdocs%2Fcp193_Simplification_Public_Nuisance_Consultation.pdf&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ARefusal+to+serve+in+a+public+office\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-halsbury11-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-halsbury11_2-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-halsbury11_2-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a href=\"/wiki/Halsbury%27s_Laws_of_England\" title=\"Halsbury&#39;s Laws of England\">Halsbury's Laws of England</a>, volume 1: \"Administrative law\", paragraph 11 </span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-halsbury469-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-halsbury469_3-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-halsbury469_3-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a href=\"/wiki/Halsbury%27s_Laws_of_England\" title=\"Halsbury&#39;s Laws of England\">Halsbury's Laws of England</a>, volume 26: \"Criminal Law\", paragraph 469 (5th edition)</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-4\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/1975/24/section/8\">section 8, House of Commons Disqualification Act 1975</a></span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n\n<!-- \nNewPP limit report\nParsed by mw1331\nCached time: 20180910115917\nCache expiry: 1900800\nDynamic content: false\nCPU time usage: 0.068 seconds\nReal time usage: 0.092 seconds\nPreprocessor visited node count: 182/1000000\nPreprocessor generated node count: 0/1500000\nPost\u2010expand include size: 2853/2097152 bytes\nTemplate argument size: 138/2097152 bytes\nHighest expansion depth: 7/40\nExpensive parser function count: 0/500\nUnstrip recursion depth: 0/20\nUnstrip post\u2010expand size: 3028/5000000 bytes\nNumber of Wikibase entities loaded: 0/400\nLua time usage: 0.024/10.000 seconds\nLua memory usage: 1.34 MB/50 MB\n-->\n<!--\nTransclusion expansion time report (%,ms,calls,template)\n100.00%   73.731      1 Template:Reflist\n100.00%   73.731      1 -total\n 76.95%   56.738      1 Template:Cite_web\n  2.58%    1.900      1 Template:Main_other\n  2.44%    1.800      2 Template:Halsbury\n-->\n\n<!-- Saved in parser cache with key enwiki:pcache:idhash:36481700-0!canonical and timestamp 20180910115917 and revision id 846621949\n -->\n</div>"},"langlinks":[],"cate